    1. 3 Shorten Area Name

      Scenarios 3 0 0 
      In order to shorten the area name in the Html report.
As a Developer
I would like to shorten the area name by removing the beginning of the name that matches a provided string

        3. Then there should be a section under the test run name that displays area statistics
        4. And the total number of areas should show as a badge to the right of the test run name with a value of 0
        5. And the badge should show 'Areas' when the user hovers over it
        6. And the section should show the number of passed areas with a value of 0
        7. And the section should show the number of areas with skipped scenarios with a value of 0
        8. And the section should show the number of areas with failed scenarios with a value of 0
        9. And the section should show a gray bar to indicate there are no areas

      1. 3 Write Emtpy Test Run

        1. Given has the following scenarion definition 
          using System.Threading.Tasks;
using xBDD.Test;
namespace xBDD.Reporting.Test.Features.ViewTextReport.WriteToTextScenarios
{
    public class EmptyTestRun : IExecute<string>
    {
        public async Task<string> Execute()
        {
            var xBDD = new xBDDMock();
            xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = "My Test Run";
            return await xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToText();
        }
    }
}
        2. When the method is executed
        3. Then the test results written should match the template: 
          My Test Run

      2. 3 Write Run Empty Scenario

        1. Given has the following scenarion definition 
          using System.Threading.Tasks;
using xBDD.Test;
namespace xBDD.Reporting.Test.Features.ViewTextReport.WriteToTextScenarios
{
    public class RunEmptyScenario : IExecute<string>
    {
        public async Task<string> Execute()
        {
            var xBDD = new xBDDMock();
            xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = "My Test Run";
            await xBDD.CurrentRun
                .AddScenario("My Scenario", "My Feature", "My.Area.Path")
                .Run();
            return await xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToText();
        }
    }
}
        2. When the method is executed
        3. Then the test results written should match the template: 
          My Test Run

My.Area.Path
	My Feature
		My Scenario

      3. 3 Write Run Multiple Areas

        1. Given has the following scenarion definition 
          using System.Threading.Tasks;
using xBDD.Test;
namespace xBDD.Reporting.Test.Features.ViewTextReport.WriteToTextScenarios
{
    public class RunMultipleAreas : IExecute<string>
    {
        public async Task<string> Execute()
        {
            var xBDD = new xBDDMock();
            xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = "My Test Run";
            try
            {
                await xBDD.CurrentRun
                    .AddScenario("My Scenario One", "My Feature One", "My.Area.Path.One")
                    .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition"))
                    .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                    .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                    .Run();
                await xBDD.CurrentRun
                    .AddScenario("My Scenario Two", "My Feature One", "My.Area.Path.One")
                    .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition"))
                    .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                    .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                    .Run();
                await xBDD.CurrentRun
                    .AddScenario("My Scenario One", "My Feature Two", "My.Area.Path.Two")
                    .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition"))
                    .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                    .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                    .Run();
                await xBDD.CurrentRun
                    .AddScenario("My Scenario Two", "My Feature Two", "My.Area.Path.Two")
                    .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition"))
                    .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                    .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                    .Run();
            }
            catch { }
            return await xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToText();
        }
    }
}
        2. When the method is executed
        3. Then the test results written should match the template: 
          My Test Run

My.Area.Path.One
	My Feature One
		My Scenario One
			Given my starting condition
			When my action
			Then my ending condition
		My Scenario Two
			Given my starting condition
			When my action
			Then my ending condition
My.Area.Path.Two
	My Feature Two
		My Scenario One
			Given my starting condition
			When my action
			Then my ending condition
		My Scenario Two
			Given my starting condition
			When my action
			Then my ending condition

			Then my ending condition

			Then my ending condition

			Then my ending condition

      5. 3 Write Run Multiple Scenarios Same Feature

        1. Given has the following scenarion definition 
          using System.Threading.Tasks;
using xBDD.Test;
namespace xBDD.Reporting.Test.Features.ViewTextReport.WriteToTextScenarios
{
    public class RunMultipleScenariosSameFeature : IExecute<string>
    {
        public async Task<string> Execute()
        {
            var xBDD = new xBDDMock();
            xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = "My Test Run";
            try
            {
                await xBDD.CurrentRun
                    .AddScenario("My Scenario One", "My Feature", "My.Area.Path")
                    .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition"))
                    .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                    .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                    .Run();
                await xBDD.CurrentRun
                    .AddScenario("My Scenario Two", "My Feature", "My.Area.Path")
                    .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition"))
                    .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                    .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                    .Run();
            }
            catch { }
            return await xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToText();
        }
    }
}
        2. When the method is executed
        3. Then the test results written should match the template: 
          My Test Run

My.Area.Path
	My Feature
		My Scenario One
			Given my starting condition
			When my action
			Then my ending condition
		My Scenario Two
			Given my starting condition
			When my action
			Then my ending condition

      6. 3 Write Run Scenario With Failed Step

        1. Given has the following scenarion definition 
          using System;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using xBDD.Test;
namespace xBDD.Reporting.Test.Features.ViewTextReport.WriteToTextScenarios
{
    public class RunScenarioWithFailedStep : IExecute<string>
    {
        public async Task<string> Execute()
        {
            var xBDD = new xBDDMock();
            xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = "My Test Run";
            try
            {
                await xBDD.CurrentRun
                    .AddScenario("My Scenario", "My Feature", "My.Area.Path")
                    .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition"))
                    .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action", (s) => { throw new Exception("My Error"); }))
                    .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))

    }

{{.*}}/rl

      9. 3 Write Run Scenario With Step With Multiline Parameter

        1. Given has the following scenarion definition 
          using System.Threading.Tasks;
using xBDD.Test;
namespace xBDD.Reporting.Test.Features.ViewTextReport.WriteToTextScenarios
{
    public class RunScenarioWithStepWithMultilineParameter : IExecute<string>
    {

        {
            var xBDD = new xBDDMock();
            xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = "My Test Run";
            await xBDD.CurrentRun
                .AddScenario("My Scenario", "My Feature", "My.Area.Path")
                .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition with the following", (s) => { }, $"My{System.Environment.NewLine}multiline{System.Environment.NewLine}parameter"))
                .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                .Run();
            return await xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToText();

    }

				multiline
				parameter

			Then my ending condition
